% ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
\begin{abstract}
	Sprint planning requires balancing value, effort, risk, skills, and dependency
	constraints under strict capacity limits, yet many practical workflows still rely
	on manual ranking or opaque heuristics. This paper presents \textbf{ApexS}, an
	explainable, context-aware sprint planning system implemented as an end-to-end
	stack with a React frontend, FastAPI backend, Celery workers, and a PuLP/CBC MILP
	optimization core.
	
	The implemented pipeline combines contextual weight initialization from historical
	sprint statistics, logistic-regression-based learning of urgency/value/alignment
	weights for a binary completion target, hard-constraint optimization with explicit
	toggles for capacity, risk, skill, and dependency constraints, and deterministic
	story-level explanations for both selected and rejected items.
	
	Evaluation uses four frozen cleaned datasets (Spring XD, Usergrid, Aurora, and
	TAWOS), totaling 18,036 stories and 486 sprint groups. Experiments are executed
	with multiple seeds and include four baselines: fixed-weight MILP, context-only
	MILP, greedy feasible ranking, and random feasible selection. Under identical
	capacity and risk settings, learned MILP consistently improves delivered value over
	greedy and random baselines across all datasets, while preserving traceable
	feasibility behavior and explicit rejection causes.
	
	The principal contribution is a repository-grounded integration of adaptive
	weighting, hard-constraint optimization, and auditable explanation generation in a
	single deployable decision-support workflow.
\end{abstract}

\begin{IEEEkeywords}
	agile sprint planning, mixed-integer linear programming, explainable AI for
	software engineering, Jira datasets, decision support systems, software engineering
	analytics, logistic regression, backlog optimization, constraint satisfaction
\end{IEEEkeywords}

% ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}

Because sprint planning determines which work items a software team will attempt
during an upcoming iteration, the quality of that decision directly governs
both delivery pace and stakeholder trust.
Despite its importance, the underlying choice process is seldom treated as a
structured optimization-and-explanation problem.
Balancing business value, time pressure, implementation effort, technical risk,
required skill sets, and inter-story dependency feasibility is already challenging;
maintaining enough transparency for product owners and Scrum masters to accept the
outcome makes the problem harder still.
In practice, these determinations are routinely handled through manual triage,
spreadsheet-based scoring, or rudimentary ranking rules---approaches that become
progressively unreliable as the backlog scales or as historical sprint records
accumulate without being operationalized.

Earlier studies have established that formal optimization can strengthen agile
planning decisions, and that richer project datasets raise both decision quality and
empirical credibility \cite{ase2024, agile-mo, tawos, jira-dataset}.
Concurrently, explainability has gained prominence as an engineering-tool requirement
because project stakeholders must be able to trace and evaluate the rationale behind
automated decisions \cite{xai-slr-se, xai-survey, explanation-matters}.
Despite this convergence of interest, the literature contains no end-to-end
implementation that unifies learned team behavior, binding operational constraints,
and per-story explanations within a single deployable planning loop.

\textbf{ApexS} targets that unresolved gap.
The system was designed around four guiding principles.
\emph{Context-awareness} requires that historical sprint records shape the relative
importance assigned to urgency, value, and alignment in the objective function.
\emph{Constraint-consistency} requires that infeasible stories be eliminated or
constrained before the selection stage, not penalized as soft terms afterward.
\emph{Explainability} requires that both acceptance and rejection decisions be
auditable at the individual story level through human-readable justifications and
confidence scores.
\emph{Operationality} requires that the entire workflow---upload, optimization,
explanation review, plan approval, and export---be completable without leaving the
application.

Building on the ASE~2024 context-aware sprint planning baseline \cite{ase2024},
ApexS introduces four capabilities that were absent from that prior work:
team-specific weight learning from historical outcomes, four simultaneous hard
constraints within a single ILP formulation, per-story bidirectional explainability,
and a complete approval-and-export decision support loop.

Three research questions sharpen the empirical focus.
\textbf{RQ1}~(Feasibility): can a learned-weight MILP formulation produce plans
that remain operationally feasible under realistic capacity, risk, skill, and
dependency constraints?
\textbf{RQ2}~(Explainability): does the implemented explanation layer provide
complete and decision-specific coverage for both accepted and rejected stories?
\textbf{RQ3}~(Comparative): how does learned MILP compare with fixed-weight MILP,
context-only MILP, greedy feasible ranking, and random feasible baselines on
representative sprint-ready backlogs?
Because the repository implements learning, optimization, explanation, and workflow
support as distinct yet connected stages, the evaluation is conducted at the same
level of granularity as the codebase itself.

The contributions of this work are:
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*,itemsep=1pt,topsep=2pt]
	\item A full-stack sprint planning system unifying dataset ingestion, context
	      extraction, weight learning, MILP optimization, explanation generation, and
	      approval/export workflow within a single reproducible Docker Compose stack.
	\item A repository-grounded planning formulation that faithfully mirrors the
	      implemented code path, encompassing status-aware feasibility filtering, risk
	      gating, skill compatibility checking, and dependency constraints.
	\item A quantitative evaluation with seeded runs across four datasets, including
	      baseline comparisons, constraint ablations, and runtime measurements exported
	      as machine-readable artifacts.
	\item A well-defined novelty layer over earlier sprint-planning research: team-specific
	      weights inferred from historical outcomes, bidirectional explanation output
	      covering both selected and rejected stories, and an end-to-end decision-support
	      loop rather than a standalone optimizer.
	\item A validated dataset processing pipeline comprising converter scripts, multiple
	      pre-validated upload-ready datasets, and a normalized schema aligned with the
	      Jira export format used in industrial practice.
\end{enumerate}

The remainder of this paper is organized as follows.
Section~\ref{sec:related} surveys related work.
Section~\ref{sec:requirements} describes the system requirements and process model.
Section~\ref{sec:methodology} presents the architecture and methodology.
Section~\ref{sec:results} reports evaluation results and discussion.
Section~\ref{sec:conclusion} concludes with future directions.

% ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
\section{Literature Survey}
\label{sec:related}

Automated support for sprint planning has evolved from early heuristic formulations
toward increasingly context-sensitive backlog selection strategies.
A multi-objective agile project planning model proposed by Ozcelikkan~\emph{et al.}
established that mathematically grounded methods can surpass naive prioritization
when objectives compete \cite{agile-mo}.
Subsequently, Kula~\emph{et al.} introduced context-aware sprint plan generation,
demonstrating that planning quality rises when project context is explicitly modeled
rather than held constant \cite{ase2024}.
Although these contributions motivate formal optimization, neither fully resolves the
engineering challenge of surfacing decisions transparently, collecting systematic
evidence, and embedding the planner within a usable workflow.

The feasibility of applying mathematical programming to agile planning was
separately confirmed by Chaves~\emph{et al.}, who formulated backlog selection
as a constrained combinatorial problem and addressed it with a Lagrangian heuristic
\cite{lagrangian-sprint}.
Explainability and team-adaptive weighting, however, remained outside the scope of
that work.

Publicly available datasets have raised the standard for empirical evaluation in
this domain.
TAWOS supplies a structured corpus of agile open-source projects \cite{tawos},
while the Jira repository dataset assembled by Montgomery~\emph{et al.} provides
issue-level records that are particularly well-suited to backlog, workflow, and
dependency analysis \cite{jira-dataset}.
Research on intelligent software engineering in agile settings and on agile data
analytics confirms that historical project traces can support prioritization,
effort estimation, and reporting \cite{intelligent-agile, bigdata-agile}.
These studies also highlight a recurring gap: analytics components are rarely
assembled into deployable tools.

Story point estimation research is directly relevant because reliable effort signals
are a prerequisite for credible sprint planning.
Transformer-based story point estimation \cite{gpt2sp}, ensemble-based prediction
approaches \cite{ensemble-spe}, and controlled experiments with large language models
for agile effort estimation \cite{llm-effort} collectively show that machine
learning can identify consistent patterns in agile work items.
These methods, however, are oriented toward estimation accuracy rather than toward
sprint-feasibility decisions as a whole.
Systematic mappings of early estimation in agile projects reinforce the same
observation: estimation support is plentiful, while integrated planning pipelines
remain scarce \cite{agile-estimation-map}.

Story-level risk modeling constitutes an additional relevant thread.
Bug triage and defect prediction studies \cite{bugtriage-deeplearning} establish that
historical defect records can serve as proxy signals for per-story risk---a property
that ApexS exploits through its dataset converter pipeline.
Embedding those risk signals directly into a planning optimizer, rather than
treating risk prediction as a separate downstream task, represents one of the open
engineering challenges that this work begins to address.

The necessity of explainability in software engineering tools is increasingly
well-documented.
General XAI surveys catalogue the inherent tension between model performance and
interpretability \cite{xai-survey}, and empirical studies confirm that user trust is
conditioned on both explanation quality and task context \cite{explanation-matters}.
A systematic review specific to software engineering by Mohammadkhani~\emph{et al.}
identifies a pronounced shortage of explainable systems that move beyond theoretical
proposals and operate on real engineering data \cite{xai-slr-se}.
ApexS occupies this identified gap: it couples learned adaptive weighting, hard
constraint enforcement, and user-visible explanations in a system that can be
deployed, tested, and audited against real project data.

Table~\ref{tab:related-comparison} situates ApexS relative to representative prior
systems across the four dimensions that define its core design objectives.

\begin{table}[t]
	\caption{Positioning ApexS Against Representative Prior Work}
	\label{tab:related-comparison}
	\centering\small
	\begin{tabularx}{\columnwidth}{lYYYY}
		\toprule
		System                              & Team-adapt   & 4 constraints & Bidirectional explain & Full workflow \\
		\midrule
		ASE 2024 \cite{ase2024}             & Partial      & No            & No                    & No            \\
		Lagrangian \cite{lagrangian-sprint} & No           & Partial       & No                    & No            \\
		MO-agile \cite{agile-mo}            & No           & No            & No                    & No            \\
		GPT2SP \cite{gpt2sp}                & No           & No            & No                    & No            \\
		\textbf{ApexS (this work)}          & \textbf{Yes} & \textbf{Yes}  & \textbf{Yes}          & \textbf{Yes}  \\
		\bottomrule
	\end{tabularx}
\end{table}

Across these research threads, the unresolved challenge is not purely one of
algorithmic accuracy.
The harder problem is how to convert noisy project history into a plan that is
simultaneously feasible, inspectable, and usable within an actual sprint workflow.
ApexS contributes at precisely that level: rather than presenting isolated prediction
or optimization components, it operationalizes the complete analytics pipeline.

