\section{System Requirements and Process Model}
\label{sec:requirements}

\subsection{Functional Requirements}

System specification followed the IEEE~830 SRS format prior to implementation.
Eight functional requirements (F1--F8) govern the design:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*,itemsep=1pt,topsep=2pt,label={F\arabic*.}]
	\item \emph{Dataset Import}: upload historical sprint data in CSV format with
	      schema validation (required columns: \texttt{story\_id},
	      \texttt{story\_points}, \texttt{business\_value}, \texttt{risk\_score}),
	      followed by deterministic normalization of \texttt{depends\_on},
	      \texttt{required\_skill}, and \texttt{status} fields.
	\item \emph{Context Analysis}: compute sprint velocity, completion rate, skill
	      distribution, and feature correlations from the uploaded history.
	\item \emph{Weight Learning}: derive team-specific urgency, value, and alignment
	      weights from historical completion outcomes.
	\item \emph{MILP Optimization}: produce optimized sprint backlogs subject to
	      configurable constraints, with a greedy fallback activated when the MILP
	      solver is unavailable or cannot reach an optimal solution.
	\item \emph{Risk Awareness}: apply a configurable risk-score threshold as a hard
	      feasibility gate before the optimization stage and carry the filtered set
	      through to selection.
	\item \emph{Explainability}: emit per-story acceptance and rejection reasons,
	      contribution breakdowns, and confidence scores.
	\item \emph{Modification}: re-execute optimization from an existing plan with
	      updated constraint parameters to enable what-if analysis.
	\item \emph{Reporting}: expose velocity trends, value delivery trends, risk
	      profiles, and learning-model diagnostics.
\end{enumerate}

Table~\ref{tab:req-traceability} maps each requirement to the implementing system
component.

\begin{table}[t]
	\caption{Requirements-to-Implementation Traceability Matrix}
	\label{tab:req-traceability}
	\centering\small
	\begin{tabularx}{\columnwidth}{lY}
		\toprule
		Requirement         & Implementing Component                             \\
		\midrule
		F1 Import Data      & \texttt{ContextExtractor} + Dataset Upload API     \\
		F2 Context Analysis & \texttt{ContextExtractor}                          \\
		F3 Learn Weights    & \texttt{WeightLearningModel} (logistic regression) \\
		F4 Optimization     & \texttt{OptimizationEngine} (PuLP/CBC)             \\
		F5 Risk Awareness   & Strict pre-optimization feasibility filter         \\
		F6 Explainability   & \texttt{ExplainabilityEngine}                      \\
		F7 Modification     & Plans API + \texttt{OptimizationEngine} re-run     \\
		F8 Reporting        & Reports API + Report Viewer UI                     \\
		\bottomrule
	\end{tabularx}
\end{table}

\subsection{Non-Functional Requirements}

Several non-functional constraints govern system behavior.
Performance requires plan generation within 60~s for backlogs containing up to 100
stories.
Reliability requires a best-effort fallback plan upon infeasibility rather than a
server-side error.
Usability requires that human-readable explanations be accessible from both the API
and the UI.
Portability requires single-command full-stack deployment through Docker Compose.
Security requires JWT-based role-level authentication covering Scrum Master and
Product Owner roles.

\subsection{Process Model}

Because ApexS is designed to function \emph{within} the Scrum framework---targeting
the Sprint Planning ceremony in particular---development naturally adopted the
\emph{Agile Scrum} process model.
This alignment was deliberate: the same incremental sprint structure used in the
target domain was applied to the development work itself.
Six sequential development sprints corresponded to six implementation phases: Sprint~0
(infrastructure and scaffolding), Sprint~1 (data ingestion and context extraction),
Sprint~2 (MILP engine), Sprint~3 (explainability), Sprint~4 (frontend integration),
and Sprint~5 (evaluation and documentation).

Validating design decisions at each increment, rather than accumulating risk toward
a single integration point, was a key benefit of this alignment.
Sequential heavyweight models such as Waterfall were considered and rejected because
research requirements evolved as empirical results became available.
A full microservices architecture was likewise ruled out on grounds of operational
simplicity: the six-service Docker Compose configuration delivers sufficient service
isolation without the inter-service contract management overhead that microservices
would impose.

% ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
\section{Methodology}
\label{sec:methodology}

\subsection{System Architecture and Overview}

Five architectural layers structure the ApexS platform:
(1)~\emph{Presentation Layer}---a React~18 and TypeScript frontend built with Vite
and React Query;
(2)~\emph{Application Layer}---a FastAPI service exposing a versioned REST API
at \texttt{/api/v1};
(3)~\emph{Worker Layer}---a Celery task backed by a Redis broker that executes the
planning pipeline asynchronously;
(4)~\emph{Data Layer}---a SQLAlchemy ORM operating over SQLite in development or
PostgreSQL in production, with schema evolution managed by Alembic; and
(5)~\emph{Storage Layer}---MinIO for CSV and JSON file objects.

Six services constitute the Docker Compose stack: \texttt{frontend},
\texttt{backend}, \texttt{db} (PostgreSQL), \texttt{redis}, \texttt{minio}, and
\texttt{celery\_worker}.
Issuing a single \texttt{docker compose up --build} command brings the system online
at four entry points: the frontend UI at \texttt{:5173}, the backend API at
\texttt{:8000}, Swagger documentation at \texttt{:8000/docs}, and the MinIO console
at \texttt{:9001}.

Eighteen versioned REST endpoints distributed across seven route groups---\texttt{/auth},
\texttt{/teams}, \texttt{/datasets}, \texttt{/sprints}, \texttt{/stories},
\texttt{/plans}, and \texttt{/reports}---are exposed by the backend.
Plan generation follows an asynchronous pattern: \texttt{POST /plans/generate}
returns a \texttt{job\_id} immediately, and the caller polls
\texttt{GET /plans/status/\{job\_id\}} until \texttt{status = done}.
This design prevents blocking the UI during ILP solve time and enables real-time
progress reporting.

\begin{figure*}[t]
	\centering
	\IfFileExists{figs/architecture.png}{%
		\includegraphics[width=0.97\textwidth]{figs/architecture.png}%
	}{%
		\placeholderwidefig{Five-layer modular architecture of the ApexS sprint planning stack.}{Replace with actual architecture diagram before submission.}%
	}
	\caption{Five-layer modular architecture of the ApexS sprint planning stack.
		Layers from top to bottom: (1)~Presentation Layer with React~18 frontend,
		(2)~Application Layer exposing seven FastAPI route groups for team/dataset/plan
		management, including four core application services (Optimization via
		PuLP/CBC, Explainability engine, Context extractor, and Weight learner),
		(3)~Worker Layer using Celery with Redis broker for long-running planning tasks,
		(4)~Data Layer with SQLAlchemy ORM and Alembic-managed migrations, and
		(5)~Storage Layer using PostgreSQL, Redis, and MinIO.
		The planning pipeline (dataset upload $\rightarrow$ context extraction
		$\rightarrow$ weight learning $\rightarrow$ MILP optimization $\rightarrow$
		explanation generation) executes asynchronously in the Celery worker, with
		progress exposed through the Plans API.}
	\label{fig:architecture}
\end{figure*}

Four backend services are central to the paper's claims and are directly
implemented in the repository.
\texttt{ContextExtractor} derives contextual weights and team statistics from
historical sprint records.
\texttt{WeightLearningModel} fits a logistic regression model over story points,
business value, and risk score to obtain urgency, value, and alignment weights.
Binary story selection is performed by \texttt{OptimizationEngine} using PuLP/CBC.
\texttt{ExplainabilityEngine} emits human-readable justifications together with
contribution fields and confidence scores for every planning decision.
These stages are orchestrated by a planning worker that reports progress through
eight named transitions: \texttt{loading}, \texttt{syncing\_stories},
\texttt{loading\_history}, \texttt{extracting}, \texttt{learning},
\texttt{optimizing}, \texttt{explaining}, and \texttt{done}.

\subsection{Dataset Processing Pipeline}

To accommodate heterogeneous Jira-style exports, the repository supplies dataset
conversion and cleaning scripts that transform raw source files into the normalized
schema expected by the planner.
Common source fields such as \texttt{issue key}, \texttt{summary}, \texttt{priority},
and \texttt{story points} are mapped to a standardized eleven-column CSV:
\texttt{story\_id}, \texttt{title}, \texttt{description}, \texttt{story\_points},
\texttt{business\_value}, \texttt{risk\_score}, \texttt{required\_skill},
\texttt{sprint\_id}, \texttt{sprint\_completed}, \texttt{depends\_on}, and
\texttt{status}.
A separate cleaning script then normalizes status labels, derives or bounds risk and
value fields, infers required skills from textual cues, and removes duplicate
records. In the backend execution path, an additional preprocessing layer enforces
runtime consistency before optimization: dependency lists are parsed from raw string
formats (e.g., ``A,B,C''), skill labels are lowercased and whitespace-normalized,
and status values are canonicalized to prevent formatting artifacts from altering
feasibility outcomes.

For the final paper, the empirical study is restricted to four cleaned
Jira-derived datasets:
\texttt{files/cleaned\_datasets/spring\_xd\_clean.csv},
\texttt{files/cleaned\_datasets/usergrid\_clean.csv},
\texttt{files/cleaned\_datasets/aurora\_clean.csv}, and
\texttt{tawos/paper\_datasets/tawos\_apex\_clean.csv}.
Spring XD, Usergrid, and Aurora serve as supporting comparative datasets; TAWOS
functions as the primary real-world evaluation dataset owing to its substantially
larger corpus and its richer combination of sprint and dependency evidence.

Because an identical normalized schema is applied across all four files, a single
planning pipeline and a single reporting protocol suffice for the entire evaluation.
All descriptive statistics, optimization outcomes, baseline comparisons, and case
study examples should consequently be derived exclusively from these four frozen CSV
snapshots.
Corpus-level statistics are reported in Table~\ref{tab:dataset-summary} in the
Results section.

\subsection{Context Extraction and Weight Learning}

Sprint-level statistics produced by the context extractor serve a dual purpose:
they supply descriptive analytics for reporting and they initialize the
weight-learning stage with project-specific priors.
The extractor computes mean velocity over available sprint IDs, completion rate,
skill distribution, average tolerated risk among completed stories, and the
correlation between business value and completion.
Let $V$ denote mean sprint velocity, $\rho$ the value-completion correlation, $\bar{r}$
the mean risk of completed stories, and $C$ the target sprint capacity.
Three contextual components are normalized as follows:
\begin{equation}
	\begin{aligned}
		u & = \min(1,\; V/C),                     \\
		v & = \min(1,\; \max(0.1,\; \rho + 0.5)), \\
		a & = \min(1,\; \max(0.1,\; 1 - \bar{r}))
	\end{aligned}
	\label{eq:context}
\end{equation}
and subsequently rescaled so that $u+v+a=1$.
Within the implementation, these quantities become the contextual urgency, value,
and alignment weights.

A logistic regression model is then fitted by the weight learner over the features
\texttt{story\_points}, \texttt{business\_value}, and \texttt{risk\_score}, treating
\texttt{sprint\_completed} as the target.
Let $\mathbf{x}_i = [SP_i,\, BV_i,\, r_i]^\top$ and $y_i \in \{0,1\}$ denote
the completion label.
With L2 regularization, the objective is:
\begin{equation}
	\hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}} = \arg\min_{\boldsymbol{\beta}}
	\sum_i \Bigl[ -y_i\log p_i - (1-y_i)\log(1-p_i) \Bigr]
	+ \lambda \left\| \boldsymbol{\beta} \right\|_2^2,
	\quad p_i = \sigma(\boldsymbol{\beta}^\top\mathbf{x}_i)
	\label{eq:logistic}
\end{equation}
with $\lambda = 1.0$ (scikit-learn default).
To improve validity, model evaluation is performed on a held-out 20\% test split
(80/20 train-test protocol), and MAE, $R^2$ (on predicted probability), accuracy,
F1, and ROC-AUC are computed on the test partition.
Coefficient interpretation is sign-aware rather than magnitude-only: story points
and risk are expected to decrease completion likelihood, while business value is
expected to increase it. Consequently, coefficient directions are aligned to domain
semantics and transformed into non-negative importance scores that are normalized to
yield the final optimization weights $w_u, w_v, w_a$ satisfying
$w_u + w_v + w_a = 1$.
For robustness, two guarded fallbacks are used in production: if the training sample
size is below 10 rows, or if numerical/model dependencies are unavailable, context
weights are reused; if target variance in the test split is zero, $R^2$ is omitted.
These safeguards prevent unstable estimates from propagating into the optimization
stage.
The learned quantities observed in the current evaluation snapshot are summarized in
Table~\ref{tab:learning-metrics}.

\begin{table}[t]
	\caption{Learning and Context Metrics Derived from Evaluation Runs}
	\label{tab:learning-metrics}
	\centering\small
	\begin{tabularx}{\columnwidth}{lY}
		\toprule
		Metric                       & Observed value                                           \\
		\midrule
		Mean MAE across runs         & 0.3027                                                   \\
		Mean $R^2$ across runs       & 0.1512                                                   \\
		Mean F1 across runs          & 0.8763                                                   \\
		Mean ROC-AUC across runs     & 0.7075                                                   \\
		Context urgency weight range & 0.3602--0.4503                                           \\
		Context value weight range   & 0.3252--0.3461                                           \\
		Context alignment range      & 0.2036--0.3146                                           \\
		Model type                   & Logistic regression (80/20 hold-out, sign-aware mapping) \\
		\bottomrule
	\end{tabularx}
\end{table}

The learned-weight profile varies across datasets, which confirms that the model
adapts to project-specific completion behavior rather than imposing a fixed
importance pattern. This variability directly influences downstream selection
outcomes under identical constraint settings.

\subsection{Pipeline Semantics}

Rather than operating as a monolithic black box, the implemented planning pipeline
follows a strict eight-step progression: (1)~loading the most recently uploaded
dataset, (2)~upserting sprint stories into persistent storage, (3)~aggregating
historical uploads for the team, (4)~extracting context, (5)~learning weights,
(6)~solving the MILP, (7)~generating explanations, and (8)~persisting the resulting
plan and explanation records.
Because each stage produces inspectable artifacts, this sequencing is important for
research validity: the system supports analysis at both the workflow level and the
algorithmic level.

Algorithm~\ref{alg:pipeline} provides a high-level pseudocode representation of
the planning task, including runtime preprocessing and post-solve validation
artifacts, which map one-to-one to the named progress states visible in the
frontend.

\begin{algorithm}[t]
	\caption{ApexS Asynchronous Planning Pipeline}
	\label{alg:pipeline}
	\begin{algorithmic}[1]
		\Require dataset $D$, sprint config $(C, \tau, \mathcal{S}, \text{goal})$, stories $\mathcal{B}$
		\Ensure sprint plan $P$, explanations $E$
		\State \textbf{progress} $\leftarrow$ \texttt{loading}
		\State $D' \leftarrow \text{validate}(D)$; upsert stories $\mathcal{B}$
		\State $\mathcal{B} \leftarrow \text{preprocess}(\mathcal{B})$
		\hfill $\triangleright$ normalize status, skill, and dependency fields
		\State \textbf{progress} $\leftarrow$ \texttt{extracting}
		\State $\text{ctx} \leftarrow \text{ContextExtractor.run}(D', C)$
		\hfill $\triangleright$ Eq.~\ref{eq:context}
		\State \textbf{progress} $\leftarrow$ \texttt{learning}
		\State $\mathbf{w} \leftarrow \text{WeightLearningModel.fit}(D', \text{ctx})$
		\hfill $\triangleright$ Eq.~\ref{eq:logistic}
		\State \textbf{progress} $\leftarrow$ \texttt{optimizing}
		\State $\mathcal{F} \leftarrow \text{feasibility\_filter}(\mathcal{B}, \tau, \mathcal{S})$
		\hfill $\triangleright$ Eq.~\ref{eq:feasible}
		\State $P \leftarrow \text{OptimizationEngine.solve}(\mathcal{F}, \mathbf{w}, C)$
		\hfill $\triangleright$ Eq.~\ref{eq:objective}--\ref{eq:binary}
		\State $M \leftarrow \text{collect\_diagnostics}(P)$
		\hfill $\triangleright$ feasibility counts + score distribution
		\State \textbf{progress} $\leftarrow$ \texttt{explaining}
		\State $E \leftarrow \text{ExplainabilityEngine.generate}(P, \mathcal{B}, \mathbf{w})$
		\State \textbf{persist} $P$, $E$, $M$ to database
		\State \textbf{progress} $\leftarrow$ \texttt{done}; \textbf{return} $(P, E)$
	\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

This design also improves traceability during demonstration and evaluation.
Progress transitions exposed in the frontend map one-to-one to worker stages; the
reports endpoint surfaces learned-model diagnostics; and the explainability
endpoints expose the final decision rationale.
Viewed as a research artifact, ApexS is therefore more than an optimizer benchmark:
it is a complete, empirically grounded system.

\subsection{Optimization Model}

The optimization stage closely follows the repository implementation.
Candidate stories are first subjected to feasibility conditions:
\begin{equation}
	\mathcal{F} =
	\left\{
	i \in \mathcal{B} \;\middle|\;
	\text{status}_i \notin \mathcal{N},\;
	r_i \le \tau,\;
	\text{skill}_i \in \mathcal{S} \;\text{or empty},\;
	\text{dep}(i) \subseteq \mathcal{B}
	\right\}
	\label{eq:feasible}
\end{equation}
where $\mathcal{B}$ is the backlog slice, $\mathcal{N}$ denotes the set of
non-plannable statuses (\texttt{done}, \texttt{closed}, \texttt{resolved},
\texttt{completed}), $\tau$ is the risk threshold, and $\mathcal{S}$ is the
available-skill set. Importantly, dependency feasibility is strict: if any declared
dependency is absent from the current candidate pool, the story is rejected before
optimization.

Over the feasible set $\mathcal{F}$, ApexS solves a normalized objective:
\begin{equation}
	\max \sum_{i \in \mathcal{F}} x_i
	\Bigl(
	w_v \cdot \widetilde{BV}_i +
	w_u \cdot (1 - \widetilde{SP}_i) +
	w_a \cdot (1 - r_i)
	\Bigr)
	\label{eq:objective}
\end{equation}
subject to:
\begin{align}
	\sum_{i \in \mathcal{F}} x_i \cdot SP_i & \le C \label{eq:capacity}                                      \\
	x_i                                     & \le x_j, \quad \forall j \in \text{dep}(i) \label{eq:deps}     \\
	x_i                                     & \in \{0,1\}, \quad \forall i \in \mathcal{F} \label{eq:binary}
\end{align}
where $\widetilde{SP}_i = \min(1, SP_i/13)$ and
$\widetilde{BV}_i = \min(1, BV_i/10)$ denote normalized effort and value,
$r_i \in [0,1]$ is the risk score (clamped if needed), and $C$ is sprint capacity.
All feature terms and the weighted aggregate are bounded to $[0,1]$ to ensure
numerical stability and comparability across datasets.

Two implementation choices are particularly consequential.
First, risk thresholding, skill compatibility, and status filtering are realized as
hard feasibility gates applied before optimization rather than as soft penalty
terms. This deliberate engineering decision reduces the MILP search space and
renders rejection reasons unambiguous.
Second, dependency logic is encoded through binary implication constraints.
Together, these choices ensure that rejected stories can be attributed to
concrete, traceable causes---risk excess, skill mismatch, or unmet
dependencies---rather than opaque score differences.

When the MILP problem is infeasible (for instance, when all feasible stories
individually exceed capacity), the system activates a greedy fallback: stories are
ranked by descending objective score, selected while preserving both capacity and
dependency validity, and a warning is emitted in the result payload
(``MILP failed $\rightarrow$ using greedy approximation'').
This fallback preserves the Reliability non-functional requirement (F4): a usable
planning artifact is always produced, regardless of how extreme the constraint
configuration may be.

\subsection{Explainability and Decision Support Loop}

One explanation record is generated per story by the explanation engine,
covering both selected and rejected items.
To preserve semantic consistency, explanation contributions are computed from the
same normalized scoring components used by the optimization stage
(normalized value, normalized effort complement, and risk complement) rather than
from an alternate heuristic.
For selected stories, contribution-style fields are computed from weighted business
value, weighted risk impact, and an effort-derived alignment signal, together with
a confidence score derived from the same bounded objective used by the optimizer:
\begin{equation}
	\text{conf}_i =
	\text{clip}_{[0,1]}\!\left(
	w_v \widetilde{BV}_i + w_u(1-\widetilde{SP}_i) + w_a(1-r_i)
	\right)
	\label{eq:confidence}
\end{equation}
Natural-language text is subsequently synthesized from observable conditions such
as high business value, low risk, and efficient effort utilization.
For rejected stories, one of five rejection patterns is emitted in descending
precedence order: (1)~risk threshold exceeded, (2)~required skill unavailable,
(3)~unmet dependency, (4)~sprint capacity exceeded, or (5)~lower priority than
selected stories. Preprocessed status and skill labels are reused in this stage so
that rejection narratives match feasibility decisions exactly.

The architectural novelty of this design lies in its integration depth.
Explainability is not a post-hoc dashboard appended to an optimizer.
Instead, explanation retrieval is embedded within the same API surface that supports
plan generation, pagination, approval, and export.
The frontend complements this integration with a paginated rejected-story table, a
value-versus-risk scatter chart, and per-story explanation cards.
The result is a closed decision loop spanning the full
\emph{upload~$\to$~generate~$\to$~explain~$\to$~approve~$\to$~export} lifecycle.

