\subsection{Case Study Analysis}

The final evaluation component presents a compact qualitative planning example
designed to make the ApexS decision logic easy to inspect.
Its purpose is not to replace the quantitative evaluation; rather, it illustrates
how optimization output and explanation output can be jointly interpreted at the
story level.
A small, mixed set of selected and rejected stories drawn from one generated sprint
plan, each accompanied by the short explanation emitted by ApexS, constitutes the
recommended format.

The repository-backed implementation already supplies operational evidence that this
explanation layer is meaningful in practice.
Across the finalized evaluation runs, the explainability engine achieved full
story-level coverage for both selected and rejected items, with rejection reasons
tied explicitly to feasibility or prioritization causes.
In concrete terms, the layer makes it possible to justify why a high-value story may
still be deferred in favor of a smaller, lower-risk, more feasible alternative.

\begin{table*}[t]
	\caption{Illustrative ApexS Case Study From One Generated Sprint Plan}
	\label{tab:case-study}
	\centering\scriptsize
	\begin{tabularx}{\textwidth}{l>{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{2.5in}cccccY}
		\toprule
		Story ID   & Title                                                                & SP & BV   & Risk & Skill    & Sel. & ApexS explanation                                                     \\
		\midrule
		MESOS-2216 & The ``configure'' phase breaks with the IBM JVM.                     & 1  & 7.20 & 0.65 & DevOps   & Y    & Selected by weighted value-risk-effort objective under constraints.   \\
		MESOS-2334 & Tasks get stuck in TASK\_STAGING after a network decode error.       & 1  & 6.98 & 0.54 & Backend  & Y    & Selected by weighted value-risk-effort objective under constraints.   \\
		MESOS-3461 & Update Python test framework support for quiesce/revive offer calls. & 1  & 6.83 & 0.48 & Testing  & Y    & Selected by weighted value-risk-effort objective under constraints.   \\
		XD-1       & HDFS ItemWriter.                                                     & 1  & 5.98 & 0.54 & Database & N    & Rejected due to sprint capacity after higher-priority feasible picks. \\
		XD-2       & HDFS core writing helper classes.                                    & 1  & 5.90 & 0.52 & Database & N    & Rejected due to sprint capacity after higher-priority feasible picks. \\
		\bottomrule
	\end{tabularx}
\end{table*}

\paragraph{Implementation Robustness.}
Additional supporting evidence indicates that ApexS behaves as a genuine system
artifact rather than an isolated optimizer script.
The recorded verification snapshot reports 18 passing unit tests for the updated
weight-learning, optimization, and explainability paths. The updated backend
validation harness additionally executes
the full context$\rightarrow$weights$\rightarrow$optimization pipeline on
\texttt{tawos\_apex\_clean.csv} and records learned weights, learning metrics,
selected-story count, total delivered value, and average selected risk, providing a
compact regression check for pipeline consistency.

\paragraph{Interpretation.}
Considered jointly, the results address all three research questions raised in
Section~\ref{sec:intro}.
Constraint-consistency under varying capacity, risk, and skill settings is
established by the planning scenarios; the baseline comparison shows that the
learned objective improves upon greedy and random feasible ranking; and full decision
coverage is achieved by the explanation layer across the finalized evaluation runs.
The most prominent quantitative pattern is that the learned weights concentrate
most of the objective emphasis on the alignment/risk dimension, rendering the
system conservative by construction.
Such conservatism is desirable when spillover and execution risk carry high costs,
but it also motivates the modify-and-rerun workflow so that teams can negotiate the
final trade-off rather than accept a statically imposed policy.

\paragraph{Validity Considerations.}
The reported evidence warrants careful interpretation.
Internal validity is constrained by reliance on frozen historical CSV snapshots
rather than live industrial planning sessions.
Construct validity depends on the fidelity of the derived business-value and risk
proxies.
The inclusion of TAWOS, Spring XD, Usergrid, and Aurora in the evaluation layout is
the primary mechanism for addressing external validity.
Reproducibility validity remains a concern because local reruns are susceptible to
variability in dependency completeness, database initialization, and operating-system
permissions.

% ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

This work has introduced \textbf{ApexS}, an explainable, context-aware sprint
planning system whose principal contribution is \emph{integration}: four previously
separate capabilities---team-specific weight learning, constraint-enforced MILP
selection, bidirectional story-level explanation generation, and end-to-end workflow
support from dataset ingestion to Jira-compatible export---are unified within a
single, deployable Docker Compose stack.
Historical sprint data is converted into context; context drives adaptive weight
inference; those weights govern binary story selection under binding operational
constraints; and the resulting decisions are rendered transparent through explanation,
approval, and export mechanisms, all accessible without leaving the application.

Repository-grounded evidence confirms that the system is both usable and
analytically meaningful.
Across the evaluation snapshot, the learning stage achieves nontrivial signal
under held-out evaluation (MAE measured on a test split, with $R^2$ reported when
target variance is non-zero); representative planning scenarios respond
correctly to capacity, risk, and skill perturbations
(Table~\ref{tab:planning-scenarios}); learned MILP outperforms greedy and random
feasible baselines on all four datasets and improves delivered value versus
fixed-weight and context-only MILP (Table~\ref{tab:baseline-comparison}); and explanation
coverage is complete at 100\% across the evaluated runs, with qualitative
story-level evidence captured in Table~\ref{tab:case-study}.
Backend-level feasibility and score-distribution diagnostics further improve
traceability by quantifying how many candidates are filtered per constraint class
before optimization and how scoring mass is distributed across feasible stories.
The system therefore constitutes a credible foundation for further research and for
a publication-oriented systems contribution.

Three directions remain open for future investigation.
First, \emph{cross-dataset visualization completion}: populating the full chart set
for Spring XD, Usergrid, Aurora, and TAWOS would substantially reinforce the
empirical presentation.
Second, \emph{user study}: establishing whether Scrum teams trust, correctly
interpret, and actively use the generated explanations through a controlled
experiment is necessary to advance from a systems contribution to a human-factors
finding.
Third, \emph{infrastructure hardening}: pinning all optional dependencies, completing
the migration from SQLite to PostgreSQL, and designating Celery as the exclusive
asynchronous execution path would eliminate the reproducibility risks identified in
the current evaluation.
Because the core architecture is already in place, the path forward calls for
broader empirical validation rather than fundamental redesign.

